We need to prove that for a function $f: U \to V$, the range of $f$ is equal to the set of all pairs $(u, f(u))$ in the graph of $f$. Let's think about how to approach this.

First, we need to show that $\text{range } f = \text{Ran } (\text{graph } f)$. 

The range of $f$, denoted $\text{range } f$, is the set of all values $f(u)$ where $u \in U$. 

The set $\text{Ran } (\text{graph } f)$ is the set of all pairs $(u, v)$ such that $v = f(u)$. 

So we need to show that these two sets are equal. To prove set equality, we need to show each set is a subset of the other.

Let's show $\text{range } f \subseteq \text{Ran } (\text{graph } f)$:

Take an element $v \in \text{range } f$. By definition, there exists some $u \in U$ such that $f(u) = v$. 

Now, consider the pair $(u, v)$ in $\text{graph } f$. By definition of the graph, $(u, v) \in \text{graph } f$ if $v = f(u)$. Since we have $f(u) = v$, it follows that $(u, v) \in \text{graph } f$. 

Then, by the definition of $\text{Ran } (\text{graph } f)$, which is the set of all second elements of pairs in $\text{graph } f$, we have $v \in \text{Ran } (\text{graph } f)$. 

So $\text{range } f \subseteq \text{Ran } (\text{graph } f)$.

Now let's show $\text{Ran } (\text{graph } f) \subseteq \text{range } f$:

Take an element $v \in \text{Ran } (\text{graph } f)$. By definition, there exists some pair $(u, v) \in \text{graph } f$ such that $v$ is the second element of this pair. 

Since $(u, v) \in \text{graph } f$, by the definition of the graph, we must have $v = f(u)$. 

Therefore, $v \in \text{range } f$ (since $v = f(u)$ for some $u \in U$).

Since we have shown each subset is contained in the other, the sets are equal.

